 alleviate or even eliminate poverty; as these programs compete for scarce resources, it is important to develop a clear view of their impact as tools for poverty alleviation. Targeting Investments in Children tackles the problem of evaluating these programs by examining them using a common metric: their impact on earnings in adulthood. The volume’s contributors explore a variety of issues, such as the effect of interventions targeted at children of different ages, and study a range of programs, including child care, after-school care, and drug prevention. The results will be invaluable to educational leaders and researchers as well as policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChild welfarexGovernment policyxEvaluationxUnited States. 0aChild welfarexGovernment policyzUnited StatesxEvaluation. 0aEconomic assistance, DomesticxEvaluationxUnited StatesxElectronic books. 0aEconomic assistance, DomesticzUnited StatesxEvaluation. 0aFederal aid to child welfarexEvaluationxUnited States. 0aFederal aid to child welfarezUnited StatesxEvaluation. 0aPoor childrenxServices forxEvaluationxUnited States. 0aPoor childrenxServices forzUnited StatesxEvaluation. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Patricia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurdick-Will, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeming, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Greg J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDynarski, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKearney, Melissa Schettini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKilmer, Beau, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator